phase1.code:
interface Drivable {
    void drive();

    default void honk() {
        System.out.println("Beep!");
    }
}

interface Flyable {
    void fly();

    default void honk() {
        System.out.println("Honk from Flyable!");
    }
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
}

// Class implementing multiple interfaces
class FlyingCar implements Drivable, Flyable, Swimmable {
    @Override
    public void drive() {
        System.out.println("Driving on roads");
    }

    @Override
    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Flying in the sky");
    }

    @Override
    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Swimming in water");
    }

    // Resolving default method conflict
    @Override
    public void honk() {
        Drivable.super.honk();  // Choose which default to use
        // Or provide custom: System.out.println("Super honk!");
    }
}

class AmphibiousVehicle implements Drivable, Swimmable {
    @Override
    public void drive() {
        System.out.println("Driving on land");
    }

    @Override
    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Swimming in water");
    }
}

public class MultipleInterfacesExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        FlyingCar flyingCar = new FlyingCar();
        flyingCar.drive();
        flyingCar.fly();
        flyingCar.swim();
        flyingCar.honk();

        System.out.println("---");

        // Polymorphism with multiple interfaces
        AmphibiousVehicle amphib = new AmphibiousVehicle();

        Drivable asDrivable = amphib;
        Swimmable asSwimmable = amphib;

        asDrivable.drive();
        asSwimmable.swim();

        System.out.println("--- Checking instanceof ---");
        System.out.println("flyingCar instanceof Drivable: " + (flyingCar instanceof Drivable));
        System.out.println("flyingCar instanceof Flyable: " + (flyingCar instanceof Flyable));
        System.out.println("flyingCar instanceof Swimmable: " + (flyingCar instanceof Swimmable));
    }
}

phase2.brokenCode:
interface A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from A");
    }
}

interface B {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from B");
    }
}

class C implements A, B {
    // Forgetting to resolve the conflict
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
        obj.hello();  // Which one?
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
Both A and B have a default method hello(). C inherits from both, causing a conflict.

The compiler doesn't know which hello() to use!

FIX: Override hello() in C and resolve the conflict:

@Override
public void hello() {
    A.super.hello();  // Choose A's version
    // or B.super.hello();
    // or custom implementation
}

Always resolve default method conflicts explicitly!

phase3.solution:
interface Eatable {
    void eat();
}

interface Sleepable {
    void sleep();
}

interface Playable {
    void play();
}

class Pet implements Eatable, Sleepable, Playable {
    @Override
    public void eat() {
        System.out.println("Pet is eating");
    }

    @Override
    public void sleep() {
        System.out.println("Pet is sleeping");
    }

    @Override
    public void play() {
        System.out.println("Pet is playing");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Pet pet = new Pet();
        pet.eat();
        pet.sleep();
        pet.play();
    }
}
